"29_identity_collections.mst — IdentityDictionary/IdentitySet. Strongtalk's
 own versions (IdentityDictionary.dlt/IdentitySet.dlt) are tiny: its
 HashedCollection is written generically over two overridable hooks
 (hashFor:/key:matches:), so IdentityDictionary/IdentitySet each override
 just those two.

 MACVM's Dictionary (16_dictionary.mst) and Set (22_set.mst) don't have
 that hook indirection — they call `key hash`/`=` (or `anObject hash`/`=`)
 directly inside their own scanFor: bodies. But tracing every OTHER method
 on both classes (at:put:/at:ifAbsent:/includesKey:/add:/includes:/grow/
 checkGrow/do:/size/...) shows none of them call hash/= directly — they
 all reach a key/element via `self scanFor: ...` first, dispatched
 polymorphically. So scanFor: is the ONLY place the hash/equality choice
 lives, and overriding just that one method here (reusing the inherited
 keys/vals/elements instance variables directly — ordinary Smalltalk
 instance-variable inheritance, not a private-encapsulation violation)
 is enough to correctly identity-ify the whole inherited engine: new,
 at:put:, grow, do:, size, printOn: (once given their own class name,
 below) all just work, unchanged.

 identityHash is universal (Object>>identityHash, 01_object.mst) so this
 works for any key/element type, not just the ones Dictionary/Set were
 already exercised against."

"I am a Dictionary whose keys are compared by identity (==) rather than
 equality (=): two distinct but equal objects are different keys to me. I
 hash keys with identityHash, so any object works as a key. Use me to
 attach information to particular objects — for example, mapping specific
 instances to associated data — where equal-but-separate objects must stay
 distinct. My protocol is Dictionary's own: at:put:, at:ifAbsent:,
 includesKey:, keysAndValuesDo:, and the rest."
Dictionary subclass: IdentityDictionary [
    scanFor: key [
        | cap i probe |
        cap := keys size.
        i := (key identityHash bitAnd: cap - 1) + 1.
        [ true ] whileTrue: [
            probe := keys at: i.
            (probe isNil or: [ probe == key ]) ifTrue: [ ^i ].
            i := i = cap ifTrue: [ 1 ] ifFalse: [ i + 1 ] ]
    ]
    printOn: s [
        s nextPutAll: 'IdentityDictionary ('.
        self keysAndValuesDo: [:k :v |
            k printOn: s.
            s nextPutAll: '->'.
            v printOn: s.
            s nextPut: $  ].
        s nextPut: $)
    ]
]

"I am a Set whose membership test is identity (==) rather than equality
 (=): I can hold two distinct objects that are = to each other, and
 includes: answers true only for the very objects that were added. I hash
 with identityHash, so any object can be an element. Use me to track a
 group of particular objects, such as those already visited during a
 traversal. My protocol is Set's own: add:, includes:, remove:, do:, size."
Set subclass: IdentitySet [
    scanFor: anObject [
        | cap i probe |
        cap := elements size.
        i := (anObject identityHash bitAnd: cap - 1) + 1.
        [ true ] whileTrue: [
            probe := elements at: i.
            (probe isNil or: [ probe == anObject ]) ifTrue: [ ^i ].
            i := i = cap ifTrue: [ 1 ] ifFalse: [ i + 1 ] ]
    ]
    printOn: s [
        s nextPutAll: 'IdentitySet ('.
        self do: [:each | each printOn: s. s nextPut: $  ].
        s nextPut: $)
    ]
]
